A black box in the car?
U.S. road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the decaying highway system, and believe they have found the solution in a small black box that fits in the dashboard of each car.
The devices that record every mile driven and report the information to the authorities are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and the state planning offices to revise the outdated system of financing U.S. roads.
The usually rather boring area of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertarians have allied with environmental groups and advocate that the government can use the small boxes to record the kilometres travelled – and possibly where they were travelled – and then use the information to calculate tax returns.
The tea party is horrified.
The American Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and voices a number of privacy concerns.
But while Congress cannot agree on a course of action, several states do not wait any longer.
They are currently looking at how to switch over the next ten years to a system where drivers pay per mile driven.
Thousands of drivers have already tested the tachographs, some of which are equipped with GPS monitoring.
This is really a must for our country.
“It’s not something we’ll just possibly use,” said Hasan Ikhrata, Managing Director of Southern California Assn. of Governments, who plans to record the mileage of all Californian drivers in the state from 2025 onwards.
The way we pay these taxes will change.
The technology for this is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, which is funded by the taxes Americans pay at the pump, is bankrupt.
In America, however, it is not as much as it used to be.
Cars consume less gasoline.
The state mineral oil tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 cents per litre) has not risen in 20 years.
Politicians do not dare, at high fuel prices, to raise the tax even by a single cent.
“The gasoline tax is simply not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, an expert on traffic legislation at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a mile-based payment system.
“This is the most meaningful long-term alternative,” he said.
Bureaucrats call it a mileage-based user fee.
It is not surprising that the idea is popular with urban liberals, because the tax could be used, for example, to influence driving behaviour in such a way that congestion and climate-damaging emissions are reduced.
The Californian planners rely on the system to develop strategies to achieve the state’s ambitious, legally enshrined goals on climate change.
But Pennsylvania Republican Bill Shuster, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also stated that he sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
The free marketers of the Reason Foundation are also inspired by the idea of having drivers pay for the distance travelled.
“This is not a tax that disappears in a black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. Transportation Ministers who, in a 2011 report, had urged Congress to move toward mile-based billing.
Last year, the U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project that would have included 10,000 cars.
But the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the push, responding to the concerns of MEPs from rural areas, who represent people who often have to travel many miles on the way to work or the city in everyday life.
However, several states and major cities are moving in this direction on their own.
The most committed is Oregon, which is currently recruiting 5,000 drivers for the country’s largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the mileage fees instead of the mineral oil tax to the state.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is also considering such a thing.
Illinois is testing it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transportation ministries of 17 states on the east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida), is currently investigating how to introduce the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with the equipment, drivers were skeptical of the idea that the government could track any of their movements.
“Concerns about Big Brother and things like that were a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and results management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
People didn't want it.
As the test started, Nevada’s ACLU warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to turn the tachographs into full-sized surveillance devices.”
There is no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to collect data on the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that allows the state to track the miles travelled, but not exactly when and where.
That, according to Khan, would also make the public more calm.
Hunting for this technology has led some authorities to a small startup company called True Mileage in California.
The company originally did not compete to help states with the taxation of motorists.
Rather, their goal was to gain a foothold in an emerging market for car insurance, where drivers are supposed to pay based on the miles travelled.
However, the devices she tested are also interesting for road planners, because they do not work with GPS and only provide limited information that is regularly uploaded via modem.
“People are more willing to participate if their speed and locations aren’t recorded,” said Ryan Morrison, Managing Director of True Mileage.
Major mistakes have been made in some of these public pilot programmes.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to implement this.
In Oregon, planners are experimenting with giving drivers a range of choices.
You can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they don’t choose a device at all and instead pay a flat rate based on the average miles travelled by all residents of the state.
Other agencies hope to be able to sell the concept of a suspicious public by equipping the devices with more features than with fewer.
In New York City, traffic officials want to develop a taxable device that can also be used to pay parking fees, pay insurance only for kilometres travelled, and collect speed data from other vehicles in real time, allowing drivers to avoid congestion.
“Car drivers would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits offered by the system,” the city said in a planning document.
However, some traffic planners wonder if the whole talk about paying per mile is not just a huge distraction.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay Area, officials said Congress could solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund simply by raising fuel taxes.
An additional one-off fee or an annual levy could be imposed on drivers with hybrid vehicles or other vehicles that use little gasoline, so that they also pay a fair share.
“There’s no reason for surgery if an aspirin is enough,” said Randy Rentschler, the Commission’s head of legislation and public affairs.
When we do that, hundreds of millions of drivers worry about their privacy and many other things.
