Esa decides on major space missions: missions for billions
Faraway planets, gravitational waves or black holes – experts from the European Space Agency now have to agree on two major projects that they plan to launch in the next few years.
There were 30 proposals to choose from, five are still in the race.
distant worlds.
More than 1,000 planets in other stars have already been found.
Whether there is life on at least some of them, no one knows.
The choice is difficult: Should you look for gravitational waves?
Or would you rather explore the origins of the cosmos?
Or searching for Earth-like planets and perhaps discovering extraterrestrial life?
These are the questions asked by those responsible for the European Space Agency (ESA).
For their "Cosmic Vision" programme, they are looking for ideas for two large space projects that are designed to make a decisive advance in research.
The budget for such "L-Missions" is approximately one billion euros each.
The launch is expected to be in 2028 and 2034.
In early September, the elite of European space exploration met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
Thirty ideas were discussed, five of which have now been narrowly chosen.
Numerous committees examine the proposals, check with the researchers.
In the next few days, a final decision will be made by the Scientific Programme Committee.
In total, the ESA has selected four major questions to which the missions of the Cosmic Vision programme, launched in 2007, are to find answers.
What are the conditions for the formation of planets and life?
The exact processes involved in the formation of stars from large gas clouds - and thus the formation of planets orbiting these stars - are still in the proverbial darkness.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star has planets, under what circumstances can life arise there?
In order to address this question, the space telescope "Cheops" is scheduled to launch in 2017, with which 500 already known planetary systems in our immediate vicinity will be studied more closely.
However, the possibilities are limited, Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
With larger instruments, the astronomers could map Earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres, searching for “biomarkers”: gases that are considered to be an indication of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This question should also ultimately provide information about the conditions for the emergence of life.
An important role is played by the magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field as well as the particle radiation emanating from it with the planetary system.
In our solar system, these processes can be studied by way of example.
With the "Solar Orbiter", Esa has already approved a mission of the M-Class (where the budget is about half a billion euros) for this question.
The probe is scheduled to launch in 2017 and monitor the Sun’s surface and activity closely.
Also of great interest to the researchers are Jupiter and its moons.
They want to find out what role the giant planet has played in the evolution of the solar system.
For this purpose, ESA plans to launch the first of the three L-Missions of the Cosmic Vision program.
The Juice (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) probe is expected to begin its journey in 2022.
Eight years later, it reaches Jupiter and is to study the planet's atmosphere as well as the icy moons Europe, Callisto and Ganymede.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
Space offers many opportunities to study matter under extreme conditions and thus to examine whether the laws of nature we know are still valid there.
Perhaps there are also deviations that could lead the physicists to a new theory under whose roof all known natural laws can be united.
How did the universe come into being and what does it consist of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos was created by the Big Bang.
In addition to the matter known to us, which consists of stars, planets and beings like us, there is Dark Matter, whose gravity holds galaxies and clusters of galaxies together, and Dark Energy, whose action accelerates the expansion of space.
So far, the researchers have not known which physical laws were valid in the first fractions of a second of the Big Bang, nor what Dark Matter and Dark Energy are made up of.
With "Euclid", the ESA has already approved an M-Mission, which is scheduled to launch in 2020.
With a special telescope, the probe will study the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time throughout the sky, thus allowing conclusions to be drawn about the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could make the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will remain at the end of the selection process.
According to many experts, the best odds for a permit as an L-Mission have "E-Lisa", a sophisticated concept for detecting gravitational waves.
This includes changes in the structure of space-time that Albert Einstein predicted nearly 100 years ago.
They have not been proven to this day.
Elisa could do that, hope the scientists behind the project.
The mission provides a detector consisting of two or three probes that will be stationed in space.
Unlike other systems on Earth, it could also detect gravitational waves from the Big Bang, providing new insights into the formation of the cosmos.
Four more proposals still compete for the second L mission: a large X-ray telescope called "Athena", which will explore black holes, among others, "Icy Planets", another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, "Prism", a mission to survey the cosmic background radiation, and the "Exoplanet Finder", which will investigate and detect Earth-like planets.
Already excluded are proposals for sample transport back from Mars, for the exploration of the Moon, Venus and asteroids as well as for solar physics.
