Frontier Airlines Charges for Hand Baggage
Frontier Airlines plans to demand up to $100 from passengers who want to store hand luggage on their flight.
Frontier Airlines intends to charge up to $100 for a piece of hand luggage and $2 for coffee or lemonade, even though the announcement on Wednesday read that passengers may keep the whole can.
The new fee applies to hand luggage in the luggage compartment above the seat, small bags under the seat are still free.
Frontier said it would charge $25 if the fee was paid in advance, and $100 if it was first paid at the gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the $100 fee aimed at moving travelers to take care of the payment in advance.
“We don’t want to calculate that amount,” she said.
Airlines began charging fees for the first and second checked baggage in 2008.
Passengers who tried to bypass these have therefore stuffed as much as possible into their hand luggage, which means that the luggage compartments above the seat are often overcrowded.
Fees are a way to get passengers to take less on board.
O'Malley said the new fee isn't really about making money.
It’s about Frontier’s most loyal customers, who have clearly expressed that it is becoming increasingly difficult to find space in the compartment above the seat.
Passengers who buy their tickets on the airline’s website do not have to pay.
This means that a passenger at the Frontier gate may be allowed to take a piece of baggage free of charge, but the next person will have to pay $100 for a comparable piece of baggage.
O’Malley said the Frontier website and check-in procedures would be changed so that passengers would be informed of the charge before they arrived at the gate.
The new hand luggage fee from Frontier will only come into effect in the summer, an exact date does not yet exist.
Passengers often scold baggage surcharges and other charges, but airlines like to resort to them.
They argue that transporting baggage costs money and passengers should pay for that service if they wanted it.
Many on Wall Street see the new baggage charges as a sign that airlines are taking enough money to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
However, most have so far left their fingers off of hand luggage fees.
Spirit Airlines Inc. was the first to charge for hand luggage three years ago, followed by Allegiant Air, another low-cost airline.
The only other airline with such a fee is Hungarian Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the additional fees.
He estimated in a December 2011 report that the Spirit hand luggage fee raises $50 million annually.
Sorensen, who previously held a leadership position at Midwest Airlines, recently flew with Spirit and was curious about what he would expect at the gate if passengers were faced with the company’s unusual hand luggage fee.
“The boarding process was one of the smoothest I’ve experienced in my aviation career,” he said.
I was expecting to see gnashing of teeth and tangible discussions at the gateway.
"The plane was full," he explained, "and the boarding went as if lubricated."
Frontier also follows Spirit with the 2 dollars that are required for coffee, tea, lemonade or juice.
The company stated that passengers who bought lemonade or juice were allowed to keep the whole can and coffee would be replenished for free.
Water is still free.
US Airways had briefly tried to charge for soft drinks in 2008, but reversed this seven months later after passengers complained and no other major airline followed suit.
Frontier’s move to charge for hand luggage if passengers don’t buy directly from the airline is the latest initiative aimed at redirecting customers to their own website.
Airlines pay online travel agencies such as Orbitz $10 to $25 per ticket sold.
This gives all companies an incentive to move passengers to buy directly from them instead of via an online travel agency.
Frontier, however, has gone the farthest in this area.
In September, the company began to award only half as many frequent flyer miles when booking through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, the miles were again shortened to 25 percent of the flight distance.
For this reason, a flight with Frontier over 1000 miles booked from a third party brings customers only 250 miles.
Passengers can also reserve seats exclusively for direct purchases on the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base at its Denver headquarters, but the business is shrinking and the company is losing money.
Revenue declined by 9 percent and flight capacity shrank by almost 13 percent in the first quarter, according to the financial report published Wednesday by the parent company, Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic has attempted to control the finances of Frontier as part of the sale of the company.
