He admitted to cocaine possession in a previous interview.
The lawyer was convicted after the police found out in their investigation into Scarborough that he had been in regular telephone contact with Ditta in February 2011.
Two investigators followed the suspect and saw him go to Ditta’s house and put the drugs under the lawyer’s garbage can with a 60 percent purity in a black golf glove.
Shortly after delivering the drugs, Scarborough regularly phoned Ditta, who was at dinner at the Blackburn Rovers football stadium in Ewood Park.
The lawyer returned home, picked up the drugs, and then nine messages were exchanged between the two.
In court, it was revealed that Ditta was a "regular consumer" of cocaine after tests had detected Class A drugs in his hair, wallet, and credit cards.
Ditta was later arrested, but denied taking cocaine and said he had spoken to the alleged dealer because he was his client, claiming her discussion was subject to the “lawyer’s secret.”
During his arrest, Ditta took his wallet and tried to remove a number of credit cards, but they were secured and a hair sample was taken from him.
During the police interrogation, he stated that he operates an office both at his private address and at the workplace, and clients would call him at home for legal matters.
In court, it was announced that he had called key drug trafficking actors, some of whom he had previously represented, after significant arrests and informed them of what the investigators knew about them.
Prosecutor Anne Whyte said, “A criminal attorney should know better than anyone else that you don’t break the law.”
Ditta is accused of abusing his position as a criminal attorney because he has engaged too much with certain clients.
The relationship in question is not just that of a drug dealer, but of a drug dealer who supplies his lawyer with drugs.
Some of his communications were undoubtedly legitimate, because he was the lawyer of those persons.
But that went far beyond the limits of a normal relationship between a lawyer and a client.
He countered the police investigations as much as possible so that they could continue their criminal activities.
Mr. Ditta thus brought his profession into disrepute.
He was too close to certain clients, especially Scarborough, and he allowed his independence to be compromised.
Ditta said: “If I were a corrupt lawyer, which I am not, and wanted to pass on information to Scarborough, I would not wait 15 hours, but do it immediately.”
But after the hearing, Lancashire Police Superintendent Lee Halstead said: "Mr. Ditta has taken the step from a criminal attorney to a criminal the moment he started acquiring drugs from organized criminals."
His cocaine addiction led to a hopeless compromise and made him susceptible to the motives of leading members of organized crime who commissioned him to gather valuable information about police investigations.
Lawyers must maintain the highest standards of integrity and ensure public trust and confidence.
Ditta has betrayed this trust and tried to hide behind the facade of his profession.
Lancashire’s Serious and Organised Crime Unit led the investigation against Ditta, which also led to a conviction in three cases for possession of cocaine and judicial obstruction, underlining our determination to bring criminals to justice.
This case should be a warning to criminals and shows that no one can escape the arm of the law.
We'll find you and bring you to court.
