What happens on the go with my email?
E-mail is actually an electronic letter.
In the design of the Internet service, was e-mail similar to the traditional postal service technically implemented the letter secret?
In the conception of early Internet services, the focus was on making communication possible.
Consequently, the basic technical protocols did not take care to provide a stable foundation for a sound exchange of letters.
Therefore, a conventional email corresponds more to an open postcard than to a sealed letter.
If user "Anna" sends an email to "Benni", are the computers of the two directly connected?
In the first step, Anna’s email program or browser sends the mail to the mail server of her service provider.
For example, if you have a Gmail account, it would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider that Benni uses.
On the route, the mail can run via several other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call the content to his provider.
Are traditional emails being read along the way?
Most emails are read multiple times by software robots on the go.
The sender’s provider usually checks whether the mail has a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also carried out on the receiver systems.
In addition, the providers check whether it is an annoying and unwanted spam email that is immediately deleted or at least sorted into a spam folder.
Do robots have another task?
For systems like GMail, the robot also determines the information that Google needs to place contextual advertising.
If Anna and Benni communicate via GMail about their upcoming holiday trip, Google may display corresponding links to holiday offers.
Do unknown people read the emails?
The likelihood of unauthorized people reading an email is extremely low.
In theory, however, this is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the opportunity to read electronic mail.
Law enforcement agencies and intelligence agencies also have legal means to intercept or take notice of emails.
In addition, there are possible illegal spying actions.
Is it possible to protect e-mails from co-reading?
With OpenPGP standard encryption, an email can be effectively encrypted against co-reading.
With high technical effort, it is also possible to obscure the metadata of an e-mail communication, so that it is not even easy to recognize who has communicated with whom.
How important are Yahoo and Google in the e-mail market in Germany?
According to an August 2013 investigation by Convios Consulting, Yahoo and Google play only a minor role in the mostly privately used mailboxes.
While Yahoo Mail’s shares had recently fallen, Google’s GMail was able to increase significantly.
