George Kerevan: European detachment gives the Scots the choice
A new day, a new horror story about independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland is needed to join the Schengen area as a condition for EU membership.
This provides the keyword for stories about passport controls in Berwick and a barbed wire-secured border along the Hadrian's Wall.
Indeed, the Strathclyde template pointed out the potential economic benefits that would result in more freedom of movement in the rest of Europe, but this – as expected – did not matter in the headlines.
Nor has anyone mentioned that EU member states often bend their strict rules when it is more favorable for them.
Since Scotland is not currently part of the Schengen area, continued disregard for Brussels would only be a small concession in return for what one really wants from the Scots.
Actually no story.
And one that has come so far in years that it already resembles a fossil: The first time I heard the “independence means passport control” duck at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient history.
Why should one expect an independent Scotland to dance after the European pipe?
Why exchange the London yoke for the Brussels yoke, especially now?
These are the real European news: the great plan for the unification of Europe, made after the war, has stalled.
With the euro crisis, the project Europe has officially died.
Across the EU, parties that are hostile to the EU or want to throw the euro overboard as a single currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party – founded only this year – was able to win almost five million votes in the German parliamentary elections in September and thus effectively expel the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
The current economic crisis is a turning point.
Because of the strict austerity policies imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank in conjunction with the forced jacket, in which the respective national economy is forced by the adherence to the single currency, many people believe that the project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with the fact that national governments cause excessive budget deficits – this was only the case in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has nailed its members to exchange rates that are beneficial for German exporters – and German politicians would like to let that happen.
Without the possibility of a devaluation of the local currency, southern Europe finds itself with a built-in productivity disadvantage compared to Germany.
The only option is to cut wages and public spending – spurred by Berlin.
There is a deeper European productivity problem behind the current budgetary and monetary problems.
As a result of the “green” energy directives imposed by Brussels – a code for subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times for gas compared to the United States.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we could already see in Grangemouth.
All the world’s wage fixings do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being pushed into the corner by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is stirring up, especially in France, the former cheerleader of the EU.
After the war, France’s political elite saw the EU as a vehicle to keep Germany at bay and to raise Paris on par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy and has pushed Europe into its own economic policy, with which the fraught French economy is struggling.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s right-wing, EU-hostile Front National has just won a decisive by-election and thus sent the ruling Socialists to third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote – a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split in the right-wing spectrum would automatically bring benefits to the left.
What does Le Pen do with her newly gained popularity among the white French working class?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to forge an anti-EU, anti-Community currency block in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties perform well in these elections – and this is very possible – then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point I would like to make: in the not too distant future, the growing resentment against the EU and the common currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will rather become something like the “Europe of (sovereign) nations” favored by General de Gaulle.
Germany and a few of its satellite economies may stick to the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect the UK to distance itself from this project in the hope of pleasing the United States.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific region suggests that Britain will stand alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where is Scotland in all of this?
We can decide to be a region of (in the final consequence) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – including saying to Berlin and Brussels what they can put where.
I suspect that Scotland could do quite well in a loose European union if we kept our own currency.
Cooperation with other similarly thinking countries is easier in an unfederated Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider doing the same to Norway and maintain our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – remarkably – the most successful political movement against austerity in Europe and has won a spectacular majority in 2011 due to the rejection of the proposed (and undertaken) cuts blamed on Labour Finance Minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Lib Dem coalition.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now, only to have austerity policies imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: growing up faster
African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers, research shows.
Physical changes do not immediately mean puberty
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible.
Experts believe epidemic obesity is a trigger of early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is less pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in child health and family issues.
Should a mother be worried if her daughter grows breasts and pubic hair at the age of seven or eight?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, paediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz stated that these early physical changes are relatively normal among American girls and represent a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring parents – usually this is no sign that puberty is coming quickly,” Kaplowitz explained.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and axillary hair, as well as body odor, appear in girls earlier.
Nevertheless, there was only a slight shift in the age of the menarche (the occurrence of the first menstrual period) in the last 40 years.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, slightly less than 12.75 in 1970.
"When breast development begins, it will take at least two to three years to menarch," said Kaplowitz, also author of the book "Early puberty in girls: the essential guide to dealing with this common problem."
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses.
It is controversial what actually constitutes the onset of puberty, but it applies “early” when breast enlargement is accompanied by a growth spurt before the age of eight.
In most cases, the process slows down or stagnates – something that a pediatrician can closely monitor.
With faster progress, tests by an endicronologist may be indicated so that serious problems such as tumors or cysts can be ruled out.
There are treatment methods for delaying early menstruation and defending against another consequence: premature aging of the bones, which can ultimately lead to inhibition of growth and thus small body growth in adults.
The recommendations for drug or hormonal therapy are based on the age of the child, the speed of development, the rate of growth and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is reluctant about drugs, but he admits: “Suppressing puberty can mitigate behavioral problems and girls’ feelings of being different from their peers.”
The other big problem is understandable: parents simply don’t want their very young daughters to have the period.
“They worry about the risk of pregnancy or how they handle the hygienic side,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls a woman whose daughter got her days at the age of ten.
Even though there were first signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was emotionally unprepared.
She came home scared and excited from school because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many widely published theories about the causes of early puberty.
But there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media would be the cause.
Boys, like girls, enter puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz believes that the most convincing premise is the epidemic of obesity.
He supported the conduct of a 2001 study on girls aged six to nine, which establishes a link between body fat and entry into puberty.
Other research supports this conclusion, but there are many other factors that played a role.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, early puberty seems to be influenced by all sorts of things, from economic conditions to climate and genes.
Another mystery: Although boys grow facial and pubic hair early, the trend towards full-fledged earlier puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors at the AAP conference underlined the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common even in babies and toddlers.
“We need to be careful how we identify the true onset of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to get advice from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
"This may mean that you have to have a conversation earlier than expected," Kaplowitz advised.
If you stay calm, the child usually responds well.
Girls who bloom early need the assurance that the process is a normal part of life, even if it occurs earlier than thought.
Jumbo manufacturers argue about seat width in the face of large orders
