Airbus called for an industry standard this week that requires a seat width of at least 46 cm (18 inches) in the tourist class, but U.S. arch-rival Boeing says that should be decided by the airlines.
The dispute comes at a time when aircraft manufacturers are competing to sell even larger versions of their two-engine long-haul aircraft, and expect record orders at the event from 17 to 21 November.
How the rear part of the aircraft is designed – especially if there are rows of nine or ten seats – is crucial to the stated economic results that the new “mini jumbo” design is intended to deliver.
Boeing claims its modernized "777X" can accommodate 406 people in tourist class seats that are over 17 inches wide, allowing for 10 per row.
