Faced with changing dietary habits, people are getting fatter, but airplane seats haven’t radically changed.
Between the early 1970s, when the Boeing 747 defined modern long-haul travel, and the end of the century, the weight of the male average American between the ages of 40 and 49 has increased by ten percent, according to U.S. Department of Health data.
The waist circumference of the average male American in the 21st century is 100.8 cm, according to U.S. health statistics.
Airbus says its rival sticks to a 1950s seating concept when the average body circumference of the newly-baptized “Jet Set” was narrower.
According to Airbus, investigations have shown that an extra inch (2.54 cm) per seat increases sleep quality by 53 percent.
Boeing denies Airbus’ figures on seat dimensions, saying it is not at the discretion of manufacturers to decide how airlines shape the balance between airfares and facilities.
The company also explains that, according to research, the experience in the aircraft depends on more than the seat width.
“It’s really about giving airlines flexibility so that they can do what they think they need to do to be successful,” said Kent Craver, Boeing’s cabin expert.
They don’t want us to dictate to them what makes them profitable.
They know their business better than anyone else.
For passengers it is about more elbow freedom, but for manufacturers it is increasingly becoming an issue that can have an impact on sales.
Behind the dispute lies a race for aircraft orders with an estimated volume of at least $700 billion at list prices in the coming decades, which could have a lasting impact on the export balance sheet of the US or Europe.
As Reuters first reported in July, the seat layout is the driving force behind the dispute over the new jets.
Both Airbus and Boeing claim 20 percent more efficiency per seat in their latest two-engine long-haul designs than the market leader in this segment, the 365-seat Boeing 77-300ER.
Boeing’s statements on the results depend in part on the fact that the 777X with its ten seats per row is compared to the original design of nine seats in the 777.
The increased cost per unit is still lower than that of machines currently in use with ten seats per row.
“Boeing is squeezing more seats into its aircraft to make it more competitive with our products,” said Kevin Keniston, Head of Passenger Comfort at European Airbus.
On the other hand, analysts say full cabins with ten seats per row on existing 777s suggested that many passengers opted for the narrower arrangement, which could be accompanied by cheaper airfares.
“Eighteen inches of seat width would be great for passengers, but the reality is: from an economic point of view, the Airbus offering is driven by the threat posed by the 777,” said Mary Kirby, an expert on cabin fittings, founder and publisher of Runway Girl Network.
Airbus and Boeing do not offer seats, but a catalogue of suppliers from which airlines can choose.
The world-traveling jet vendors even carry tape gauges to measure the facility against the competition.
Even though they offer comfort, all manufacturers also offer jets with high-density design for low-cost airlines and regional flights.
Airbus offers an A350 with ten-seat rows, but hasn’t sold one yet.
Until recently, Airbus has emphasized the importance of more adaptability of the cabins and offered wide seats on the aisles for some jets.
Without the support of the only other manufacturer of large modern jets, experts say the call for a new industry standard is likely to fade, but could be distracted by the wave of 777X sales.
New Anti-Nicotine Vaccine Could Stop Smoking Pleasure
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could spoil the fun of smoking.
A single dose of the vaccine could protect mice from nicotine addiction for a lifetime.
Tests on humans require further trials, which may take a few years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said the first results are good.
“We are very hopeful that this type of vaccination strategy can help millions of smokers who have tried to quit and tried all the methods available on the market, but have experienced that their nicotine addiction is stronger than these approaches,” Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to contain the genetic information needed to make nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then produce a constant stream of antibodies.
The antibodies chase the nicotine molecules in the blood and neutralize them before they reach the brain, so that a smoker does not experience a nicotine high.
In experiments, vaccinated mice administered nicotine maintained their normal level of activity.
Mice without vaccination, on the other hand, would have taken a “timeout,” the researchers explained, a sign that the nicotine had reached their brain.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
Vaccinations had to be given so often to maintain antibody levels that they were expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be significantly lower, as it transforms liver cells into antibody factories.
As Professor Crystal said, a future vaccine for humans, if he was absolutely sure, could be given to children before they were tempted to try a cigarette, thus preventing nicotine addiction.
However, it is more likely that smokers would use it to quit.
“They know then that when they start smoking again, they no longer feel pleasure in doing so because of the nicotine vaccine, and that helps them get rid of the habit,” he explains.
British scientists said the results were interesting, but at the same time warned that further research was needed.
