Australian air passengers must continue to switch off tablets and smartphones on take-off and landing, despite efforts in the U.S. to loosen the regulations for such devices.
The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) allows US airlines to change their specifications so that passengers can read, watch, or play videos on their devices during critical phases of flight, provided they are in “flight mode”.
During most of the flight, passengers are already allowed to do so, but many people find it annoying that they are not allowed to read their e-books during take-off and landing.
Australian airlines are observing the decision, which US airlines have to do a lot of work to implement, but do not have any immediate plans to change their regulations.
CASA also said it would look at the announcement, but stressed that the restrictions on the use of electronic devices in critical phases of flight in Australia continue to apply.
"The CASA currently has no specific regulations regarding the use of electronic devices in the aircraft," it said.
The subject is subject to regulations that require airlines to maintain safety at all times and passengers to follow the safety instructions given by cabin crew.
Virgin has already held talks with CASA about extending its Wi-Fi entertainment system to flights, saying that it is open to change, but that it must be initiated by lawmakers.
"We would welcome a review of the approval of electronic devices by CASA, because we are convinced that this would improve the customer experience after we now offer (wireless entertainment) during the flight," a spokesperson said.
Qantas said it will stick to the current regulations until further notice.
“Our current guidelines stipulate that electronic devices may not be used during take-off and landing, and we do not currently have any plans to change that,” the company said in a statement.
The FAA rules apply to U.S. airlines.
However, we are always interested in developments in regulations that passengers can benefit from, and we will certainly take a close look at the FAA decision and the reasons behind it.
The decision affects U.S. companies differently depending on the age of the fleet.
They must prove that their aircraft can tolerate mobile interference, and modify manuals, training materials, hand luggage programs, and customer instruction.
“After an airline has confirmed the tolerance of its fleet, it can allow passengers to use portable, lightweight electronic devices such as tablets, e-book readers and smartphones at any height,” the FAA said in a statement.
In rare cases of poor visibility, the crew will instruct the passengers to turn off the devices during landing.
The group also recommended storing heavier equipment safely under the seat or in compartments above the seats during take-off and landing.
