Pfandhäuser boom in Singapore as crisis arrives in middle class
In a pawn shop in Singapore’s Bendemeer shopping mall, Janani Amirthalinga exchanges a golden bracelet, a ring and a pair of earrings to pay the school fees of her daughters.
“My husband and I just bought a house, there’s all my money in it,” says Amirthalinga.
Although she earns $3,000 each month as an administrative employee and her husband also works, the monthly family income is not enough, she explains.
In fact, demand is so high in parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is increasing – that ValueMax, where it made its swap, became the third pawnshop listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
Pledged jewellery is not only a quick way to get money – $1,300 in Singapore in the case of Janani Amirthalinga – but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, pledge houses in Singapore demand an effective annual interest rate of 17 percent, just above the 15.4 percent required by United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
Pfandhäuser, however, offer the advantage that there is no credit check or income proof required here, which is why loans are possible faster than with banks.
That’s why millions of people in the region are turning to pawn shops as families feel the pressure of rising cost of living as well as increasing household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans due to a loose fiscal policy in the developed economies, low- and middle-income families seek out mortgage houses to make up the difference in stuttering economy.
This week, the Standard & Poor’s rating agency described rising household debt, mainly due to rising mortgages, as a risk factor for Asian banks’ creditworthiness.
Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest household debt in Asia in terms of gross domestic product.
Malaysia is at the top of the list with 80 percent of GDP, an increase of 60 percent in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high consumer debt in Thailand, which has barely emerged from a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed a continuing export weakness and a slowdown in consumer demand.
“In the end, this means that in the face of rising costs, people in the middle to lower segment (the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible,” says Song Seng Wun, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historic highs in gold prices over the past two years have intensified the trend of pledged personal items as people take the opportunity to turn family jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the items pledged in the city-state’s 200 pawnshops are gold.
People say, “The gold price looks good, let’s pledge Grandma’s gold chain and get it back next month.”
The largest Thai pawnshop operator, EasyMoney, has seen a 20 percent customer growth in its stores over the past few months.
Growth in the mortgage business is so strong that ValueMax, operating the branch in Bendemeer and 15 others in Singapore, wants to expand not only to neighbouring Malaysia – where the company operates four homes – but also outside of Asia, says Yeah Lee Ching, Managing Director of ValueMax.
The company is funding this with 60 percent of the $66 million Singapore raised this week with the IPO in Singapore.
While some lenders were caught in the crossfire because of high interest rates, Yeah explains that mortgage houses not only offered cheaper interest rates than other lenders, but also did not directly increase debt.
"Customers lend items they already own, and the liquidation of personal valuables does not increase the budget deficit," she explains.
The mortgage lease business is increasingly accepted by society as a short-term, secured financing.
Also, not all people who use mortgage loans are in financial difficulties.
Wealthy people from Singapore also come to ValueMax’s stores to pledge gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they receive up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Customers from every social class come to us.
“This includes wealthy people who lend something for a business or investment in the short term, or small businesses that need to bridge cash flow bottlenecks,” says Yeah.
Sometimes you just need money very quickly.
