Rescue package over $325 million for Tasmanian health care
The Australian government insists on the harsh conditions associated with the $325 million Australian health care bailout to ensure the state’s government can’t waste the money.
Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek has announced that the Commonwealth will take "immediate measures" to avert a crisis caused by an aging population of the island state, a higher rate of chronic diseases and system limitations.
Funding for a four-year period was decided after government consultations with independent Tasmanian MP Andrew Wilkie.
"The government has drawn up an emergency rescue package that we believe addresses the unique challenges facing the state," Plibersek said in a statement.
The $325 million package includes $31 million emergency aid for electoral services.
A further 2,600 surgeries, including orthopaedic procedures and treatments for cataracts, are to be eliminated.
In addition, there is money for day clinics in Hobart and Launceston, better post-hospital care, specialist training, mental health services, and the introduction of a system for electronic recording of health data in local hospitals.
“These investments are in line with the ideas that affected clinic staff have told me that they are the best way to improve the Tasmanian health system,” said Tanya Plibersek.
The minister insisted on a strict reporting and accountability obligation of the Tasmanian government.
The state would need to maintain its current level of funding in order to receive funds from the Commonwealth and report monthly on where the additional funds were spent.
A three-member commission will be set up to ensure that the state provides health services as effectively and efficiently as possible.
As Wilkie explained today, the $325 million would be of little use if “they were not accompanied by real reforms that bring the public Tasmanian health system to a more sustainable course.”
Nevertheless, he praised the government for responding to his request for urgent help, which he first expressed to the prime minister in early May.
"I am confident that federal aid will make a big contribution to removing the state's public health system from the worry list," Wilkie said.
According to the state government, these election benefits will largely offset the recent cuts.
But the opposition’s health policy spokesman at the federal level, Peter Dutton, believes today’s announcement is just a “patch solution.”
“We are in the current situation because the Labor State government has withdrawn $430 million from the healthcare system,” he told ABC TV.
It can’t be that a state government is ripping nearly half a billion dollars out of the system and putting 300 million into the Commonwealth and then pretending to be good news.
Dutton called on Plibersek to guarantee that not a single dollar of the bailout would be spent on additional bureaucracy.
