Syria has destroyed its ability to produce chemical weapons, according to a monitoring group
Syria has destroyed key chemical weapons and gas ammunition manufacturing facilities, the Global Chemical Weapons Monitoring Group said on Thursday, while serious clashes occurred in the north of the country near one of the sites where allegedly toxic substances are stored.
Also on Thursday, a Syrian activist group announced that more than 120,000 people had been killed since the start of the civil war almost three years ago.
The announcement of the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) came a day before the date on
November 1, which the Hague-based organization Damascus had set up to destroy or make "inoperable" all chemical weapons manufacturing facilities, including all machines for mixing chemicals into poison gas and filling ammunition.
The completion of this process, which is basically the first stage of destruction, is an important milestone in an ambitious timetable aimed at the destruction of all Syrian chemical weapons by mid-2014.
The destruction of the facilities means that Syria will no longer be able to produce new chemical weapons.
Damascus, however, has yet to begin to destroy the weapons and supplies available.
It is estimated that there are about 1,000 tons of chemicals and weapons in the country, including mustard gas and sarin nerve gas.
The announcement came at a time when fighting took place in the city of Safira on Thursday, where experts say there is a chemical weapons production facility and deposits, the UK-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights said.
The activist group, which tracks the number of dead in Syria via a network of activists, said on Thursday that 120,296 people had died.
Of these, 61,067 were civilians, including 6,365 children.
On the side of the government, 29,954 of them belonged to President Bashar Assad's army, 18,678 were pro-government fighters and 187 Lebanese Hezbollah militias.
Among the dead were 2,202 deserted army soldiers and 5,375 opposition fighters, many of them foreigners.
On July 25, the UN estimated the number of deaths in this conflict since March 2011 at 100,000.
This number has not yet been updated.
The conflict has forced about two million people to flee the country.
Assad’s troops have been fighting in Safira for weeks against the rebels, many of whom have connections to al-Qaeda groups.
The observatory said there were losses on both sides on Thursday, but did not give any details.
The fights underline the danger to which chemical weapons inspectors are exposed, as their mission to liberate Syria from its toxic arsenal is a race against time in the midst of a raging civil war.
According to the OPCW, which works closely with the United Nations, the team is “now convinced that it has seen all the important production and mixing/filling facilities mentioned by Syria and witnessed their destruction.”
Therefore, “there are currently no further inspection activities planned.”
Earlier this week, the inspectors said they had completed the first round of checks and visited 21 of the 23 sites indicated by Damascus.
Due to security concerns, the visit of two facilities was not possible, the inspectors said.
On Thursday, the OPWC stated that the two sites had been abandoned, according to Syrian statements, “and the chemical weapons program objects present there had been relocated to other listed facilities that were inspected.”
It was not immediately clear whether the site in Safira was one of the two facilities that the OPCW inspectors could not visit.
Syria has presented a plan for the complete destruction of its chemical weapons, which must be approved by the OPCW Executive Committee next month.
“I take the hat off to the bravery and courage you all have shown in fulfilling the most challenging mission ever carried out by this organization,” Ahmed Uzumcu, the director-general of the surveillance organization, said in a comment published by the OPCW.
For three years now, in this civil war, mainly Sunni Muslim rebels have been fighting against Assad’s government and its security forces, which include many members of the Alawites, to segregate Shiite Islam.
With regard to further developments, the head of the observation group, Rami Abdurrahman, said there had been a strong explosion at an air defense facility in the Syrian coastal province of Latakia on Wednesday.
The cause of the explosion is unknown, he said.
Anger over sentence for Bali bombers
Survivors and relatives of the 202 people who died in the 2002 Bali bombing reacted angrily to the verdict for the last of the instigators, who was brought to justice because, according to them, Umar Patek was to be legally shot.
Patek, who was on the run for almost ten years as one of the most wanted people in Southeast Asia, was sentenced to 20 years in prison for his role in building explosives for the bombing.
With a suspension, he could be released after 15 years.
The 45-year-old was found guilty of mass murder over the attack on two nightclubs in the popular tourist district of Kuta, in which 202 people died, including 88 Australians, and many others were injured.
