FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices in aircraft (but do not make cell phone calls)
Air travelers can now use their electronic devices to read, work, play, listen to music and watch movies from departure to landing, but not phone with their mobile phone, according to the new guidelines issued Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the United States.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented depends on the respective airline, FAA employee Michael Huerta explained at a press conference.
Airlines must prove to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated flight crew training manuals and equipment storage regulations in accordance with the new regulations.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the state of the plan, we could approve extended use of electronic devices very soon," the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers need to turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They may not restart it until the aircraft has reached an altitude of three kilometers and the captain gives the green light.
When entering the landing approach, the passengers must turn it off again and may not start it again before the plane has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are secured against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the devices even during take-off, landing and on the runway, the FAA said.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft that have been converted to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Professional Flight Assistant Association, welcomed the changes.
“If the new regulation is safely implemented – and we are working closely with the airline in this regard – both sides will benefit,” Glading said.
We are honestly tired of having to feel like guardians on this issue.
However, internet connections for browsing, exchanging emails, text messages or downloading data under three kilometers remained prohibited, the agency explained.
Passengers are asked to put smartphones, tablets and other devices in flight mode.
So still not “Words With Friends,” the Scrabble-like online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he had to publicly leave an American Airlines jet because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked at the gateway.
And heavier devices such as laptops still have to be stored, as there is a risk of injury here if they fly through the cabin.
Mobile phone calls during the flight will also remain prohibited.
The regulatory competence for telephone calls lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices on take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a security expert on national traffic issues, told CBS News that mobile phones would still be considered a risk.
“Mobile phones are really a problem, not just because they could potentially cause interference to navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that transmission from the air can also interfere with transmission towers,” Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to investigate this issue recommended last month that the government allow for a broader use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, pressure on the FAA has increased to loosen restrictions on use.
Critics such as Missouri Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill argue that there are no valid security reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies say that up to one-third of passengers forget or ignore the device.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by air passengers in 1966, after reports of interference of navigation and communication devices by passenger-carried VHF radios became known, representing the latest technology trend at the time.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA so that they don’t mind electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers Wi-Fi for several years now when the flight altitude is reached.
The aircraft adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also more insensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for increased use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices generally emit significantly less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, emit only minimal radiation when flipped over.
But when downloading or sending data, the transfer values are stronger.
One of the advocates of easing restrictions on the use of devices by passengers is Amazon.com.
In 2011, company employees loaded a passenger plane full of Kindle e-readers and took a test flight to identify problems, but were unable to detect them.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using equipment.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believes the interference from the equipment is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other committee members said there are only occasional reports of pilots speaking for a malfunction of aircraft systems through the devices, and most of them are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order the passengers to turn off the equipment when instrument landing under poor visibility conditions.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes and called them a reasonable adaptation for travelers who would now be extensively equipped with technology.
“We are delighted that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not in conflict with safety,” said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
