Scientists were able to shed more light on the connection between a dog’s tail wagging and his mood.
Earlier research had shown that happy dogs with their tails swayed more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while in nervous dogs it was the left side.
But now scientists say that other dogs can perceive and react to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: “In humans, it is well known that the left and right brains respond differently to stimuli that produce positive or negative emotions.”
Here we have tried to look at this in other species.
He also noted that in dogs, just like in humans, the right brain is responsible for the movement of the left side, and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to their species’ lateral tail wedging, researchers monitored the animals while watching these films of other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the four-legged friends and analyzed the behavior.
Probably we will soon understand why the tail moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: “We showed the dogs films with dogs – either a true-to-life version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw how an otherwise inexpressive dog moved the tail to the right (viewed from the perspective of the wagging dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail tended mainly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog waving), their heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, the dogs do not communicate intentionally with each other through these movements.
Rather, he is convinced that the dogs have learned from experience what movements they should worry about and when not.
He said: “If you have different encounters with other dogs and wagging the tail in one direction is more likely to be associated with friendly behavior and the right side is more likely to produce a less friendly behavior, then you react based on these experiences.”
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians, and trainers better understand their animal’s emotions.
John Bradshaw, an expert on dog behavior and guest fellow at the University of Bristol’s Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, said this was not the first study to examine whether left and right are important for dogs.
Last year, a team at the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right when it’s a satisfied dog.
Another research at the University of Victoria in Canada stated: “Dogs are more likely to approach a robot dog when its ‘tail’ is waving on the left rather than on the right, rather than getting restless – just the opposite than in the Italian study.”
According to his statement, the differences could therefore be that the dogs in the various studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs respond to real dogs could help, he explained.
“While there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two halves of the brain are used for different purposes, many of the details still need to be determined – and dogs are no exception,” Bradshaw said.
However, since their behavior can be easily recorded, it will probably not take long before we understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
