Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said the number of eligible cardinals is likely to have dropped by February.
He explained that a pope usually appoints as many cardinals as necessary for the number of eligible cardinals to return to 120, and as many cardinals over 80 as he wants.
The consistory next year is significant because it is the first since the election of Francis in March this year, Valero said.
At present there is a certain overhang on the part of Europe and in particular Italy.
"It will be interesting to see if the new pope will appoint cardinals from the rest of the world to restore balance," he said.
Forty percent of Catholics live in South America, but they have only a tiny number of cardinals.
The Cardinals will also be the first to be called since the formation of the Council of Cardinals founded by Francis, a group of eight Cardinals from all over the world who have the task of finding ways to reform the Church.
In the past, the pope decided everything alone.
“Now Francis has chosen these eight cardinals to help him,” Valero said.
He explained that it was “quite possible” that Francis should ask the Cardinals for advice.
