On the road through mud, rivers and jungles for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle brings free medical help to remote villages in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend treating hundreds of patients
There are not many doctors in the West African country, only one for 5,000 people
Vote here or with your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is in the top 10 of the CNN Heroes of 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other heroes in the Top 10 to vote him as CNN Hero of the Year.
The winner will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched as his ill father repeatedly lost consciousness and traveled to hospitals that did not have the means to help him.
In 1981, Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he had only one broken arm, but then an inflammation formed that spread to his brain, causing a hematoma that would affect him for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
We would have brought him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to crowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
"It's not easy," Bwelle commented.
You can leave the house at five o'clock in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, and yet you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has hardly changed since Bwelle's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor for 5,000 people, according to the World Health Organization.
In contrast, in the United States, the ratio is one doctor for 413 people.
But even if there was a doctor for them, most Cameroonians could not afford to visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line and nearly three-quarters of healthcare spending in the country is private.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” says Bwelle.
Poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
Seeing his father and so many of his compatriots suffer in Bwelle made the decision to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team performed 700 free operations last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends and provides free medical care there.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people force themselves into minibuses and drive with the corded medical equipment on the roof over unpaved terrain to the villages that need help.
Not always everything goes smoothly.
More than once, they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they will be received as heroes: a feast, singing and dancing, and the best accommodation that the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a reason to celebrate and swell – with its wide smile and limitless energy – is happy to join the joyful celebration.
The next morning, the team then begins examining hundreds of patients.
“Per trip, we treat 500 people,” says Bwelle.
They come from a distance of 60 kilometers around the village – and that on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are being treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses, or free birth certificates – a document required for school, but many poor families simply cannot afford it.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
Operations usually take place in a school, town hall or apartment; after the procedure, patients get up and go to the recreation area to make room for the next one.
The lighting for the operation and the disinfection equipment is fed by the group’s generator and so Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of the morning on Sunday.
It’s a strenuous curriculum, but the village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
“They drum all night so we can stay awake and continue our work,” says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team then drives back to the city, tired but proud of the work done.
The group – a mix of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students – performed 700 free surgeries last year and knows that their work makes a huge difference to the people they help.
One man explained that the free surgery of a hernia he had received now enabled him to work again.
“This will change the future of my family,” the man said.
In addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job, he finances 60% of his charitable work, according to Bwelle; the rest comes from private donations.
“I really don’t know when he’s sleeping,” says Katie O’Malley, who is studying medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia for the second year and volunteers in Bwelle’s group.
He’s always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can go on these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O’Malley, who come from the U.S. and Europe and support Bwelle, this is a chance to gain practical experience they would never get at home.
“We can be in surgery where we can help drain blood or hold the instruments for Dr. Bwelle,” O’Malley explains.
That would never be possible in America as a second year medical student.
Students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves and often bring donated medical supplies.
But once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes over the accommodation, transport and guidance.
“He is undoubtedly a hero,” says O’Malley.
He devotes his life to this organization and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no boundaries.
For Bwelle, the almost constant work is not a burden.
Helping others to live happier lives and thus fulfilling a promise he made to his father gives him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this work,” Bwelle says.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do it to make people laugh again and to ease the pain.
Visit ASCOVIME’s website and find out how you can help.
