Tourism: Descent to the Romans
At about 120 meters in length, a sewage channel from the Roman period is preserved below Cologne.
Those who visit Cologne will not pass the cathedral.
The two towers rise 157 metres above the sky, making it the second tallest church building in Europe.
However, few visitors who marvel at the two filigree church towers suspect that there is a lot to discover underneath the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert in the Cologne underworld.
The meeting point for his guided tours is the Cologne-Tourismus Service Center directly at the cathedral.
The tour starts quite unspectacularly: "We start in the underground car park," says Schulze.
In the seventies, the city fathers wanted a car-friendly city, and therefore from the remnants of the old city wall only what was not too big remained.
Therefore, most users of the car park today also rush past the Roman remains and only park their car.
But if you take a closer look, you will discover an archaeological site separated by metal lattice bars in the parking deck D2.
About five meters high ruins of hand-plate-sized stones can be seen.
"It is the remains of the Roman city wall, which was built in the second half of the first century AD," says Schulze.
Before it goes back to daylight, Schulze lets the participants on the upper level of the park take a look into a dark, 15-metre-deep shaft.
This is the fountain of the old cathedral, which unfortunately is also hardly noticed.
The next stop of the tour is the praetorium, and here the participants descend back into the depths.
We experience the office of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the Pretor of the CCAA.
What CCAA means, a visitor wants to know.
"The abbreviation stands for "Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium", which in good German means as much as "City of Roman Law and City of Agrippinenses, founded under Emperor Claudius at the site of the altar for the imperial cult".
And the praetorium is the former governor’s palace, the power center of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the anteroom of the exhibition, a tunnel access leads to the Roman sewage channel, which is preserved here at a length of about 120 meters.
"You can quietly walk along the so-called Cloaca Maxima if you want," Schulze encourages the guests.
Schulze still has a surprise.
After getting the key at the checkout, he leads the group to a 16-metre-deep, walkable shaft.
"We are now in the Mikwe, a ritual Jewish bath," he explains.
The Jewish community built their bath deep into the ground to get to the groundwater, which was essential for ritual washings.
To this day, in the lower end of the Mikwe, whose origins date back to the eighth century, different water levels can be read by changing levels of the Rhine.
The Mikwe will be part of an archaeological zone on the town hall square, for which construction work is to begin shortly.
However, a few years will pass until it is completed.
