John Kerry, in an unprecedented admission, said U.S. spying was “inappropriately going too far.”
John Kerry, with an unexpected admission, indicated a weakening of the U.S.'s defensive stance with respect to its surveillance programs, saying the espionage had in certain cases "goed inappropriately too far."
The Secretary of State also admitted that he, along with Barack Obama, was responsible for switching to “autopilot” when the explosive revelations by whistleblower Edward Snowden about the NSA’s espionage activities became public.
Through the leaked information, the U.S. government has fallen into a diplomatic storm of outrage on the part of its allies.
